ὅ 8. libros Sibyll. The Sibylline literature was brought to Rome, according to tradition, as early as the period of the Tarquins, and seems to have come from the Greek towns of Asia Minor through their connections in Campania at the time when Hellenic art first made its way to Rome to any great extent. As an early seat of this Sibylljne influence was at Gergis in the Troad, we may thus account for the early spread of the legends which connected the Trojan Story with the tradition of the foundation of Rome.
